PEORIA, Ill. (AP) — The Illinois sheriff’s deputy who killed  Sonya Massey  in her Springfield home last year eschewed his training and the principles of policing when he shot the Black woman who had called 911 for help, a prosecutor said Wednesday in Sean Grayson’s murder trial.  Grayson, who is white, faces three counts of first-degree murder for  shooting the 36-year-old single mother  on July 6, 2024, during a confrontation over her handling of a pot of hot water she removed from her stove.  



